Extracting the hour from the created_at variable Calculating the percent of tweets for each hour

cleaned_tweets %>%
  count(source, hour = hour(with_tz(created_at, "EST"))) %>%
  mutate(percent = n/sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = hour, y = percent, color = source)) +
  labs(x = "Hour of day (EST)", y = "% of tweets", color = "") + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent_format()) +
  geom_line()

Interpretation:

From Android, there is a lot of tweets coming at 6AM and 9PM, whereas the iPhone tweets are less concentrated at a certain time.

How often does Trump use quotes in his tweets whether the phone is an iPhone or an Android

Interpretation:

The vast majority of tweets coming from the Android phone have quotation marks, whereas the iPhone tweets do not really have. Quotes might represent sources, or exaggerated words (for example, Trump tweeting from his Android like CNN).

  • Tokenizing to analyse the sentiment of the words
  • Creating the regex pattern: identify words starting and ending with a letter (thus getting rid of numbers and links)
  • Online link to try regex pattern: www.regexr.com
  • Using the command unnest_token(): converting the strings from sentences into individual words
  • Filtering out the STOP words
# Load the tidytext package
library(tidytext)

# Create a regex pattern
reg <- "([^A-Za-z\\d#@]|'(?![A-Za-z\\d#@]))"

# Unnest the text strings into a data frame of words
tweet_words <- cleaned_tweets %>%
  filter(!str_detect(text, '^"')) %>%
  mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, "https://t.co/[A-Za-z\\d]+|&amp;", "")) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text, token = "regex", pattern = reg) %>%
  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word,
         str_detect(word, "[a-z]"))

# Inspect the first six rows of tweet_words
head(tweet_words)

Calculating the ratio of the words - Working with a logarithmic scales -by definition- requires non-zero number - In case if a word is mentioned on the Android, but has never been mentioned on the iPhone, or vice versa - Laplace transformation: Adding 1 to zeros and calculate ratios

android_iphone_ratios <- tweet_words %>%
  count(word, source) %>%
  group_by(word)  %>% 
  filter(sum(n) >= 5) %>%
  spread(source, n, fill = 0) %>%
  ungroup()  %>% 
  mutate_if(is.numeric, ~((. + 1) / sum(. + 1))) %>%
  mutate(logratio = log2(Android / iPhone)) %>%
  arrange(desc(logratio))

android_iphone_ratios %>%
  top_n(15, abs(logratio)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, logratio)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = word, y = logratio, fill = logratio < 0)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  ylab("Android / iPhone log ratio") +
  scale_fill_manual(name = "", labels = c("Android", "iPhone"),
                    values = c("red", "lightblue"))

Interpretation:

The iPhone tweets use a lot of #s and refer to the white house, whereas the Android tweets focus on words, such as ebola, which had been a frequent topic before Trump was elected President, thus this graph also conflates tweets created before-, and after his presidency.

Continue working with the filtered dataset (tweets after the announcement)

Analyzing each of the sentiments

android_iphone_sentiment <- android_iphone_ratios_post_announcement %>%
  inner_join(nrc, by = "word") %>%
  filter(!sentiment %in% c("positive", "negative")) %>%
  mutate(sentiment = reorder(sentiment, -logratio),
         word = reorder(word, -logratio)) %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  top_n(10, abs(logratio)) %>%
  ungroup()

  • Feature extraction: Creating new variables out of an unstructured data; this case the variables are: time of the day, quoted versus not, picture no picture, - Training a model that predicts whether the tweet comes from the Android or from int iPhone while Android and iPhone being the dependent variables along with independent variables, such as sentiments, whether there is a quote, whether there is a picture, whether it is a retweet with hashtags etc
  • Developing a regression analysis to predict Android vs iPhone as a function of the aforementioned independent variables (however, it does not work well with words due to grammar, sarcasm, idioms etc, but works well with time of the day)
  • Solution: when unnesting tokens, unnest couple of word at a time (might backfire)
